WEBVTT

00:08.860 --> 00:12.800
Coming up next is the Science Fiction radio show, so stay with us.

00:28.440 --> 00:33.740
This is the Science Fiction radio show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.660 --> 00:38.060
And here are your hosts.

00:43.420 --> 00:44.460
This is Daryl Lane.

00:44.700 --> 00:45.460
And David Cruz.

00:46.040 --> 00:49.860
Some of the most exciting science fiction being written today comes from the pen of Jack Chalker.

00:50.360 --> 00:54.180
And it's clear that he's a popular writer too, probably best known for the five books

00:54.180 --> 00:55.440
in the Well World series.

00:55.940 --> 01:00.000
In fact, the first novel in that series, Midnight at the Well of Souls, has sold over a million

01:00.000 --> 01:00.400
copies.

01:01.020 --> 01:06.380
Chalker's first book came out not that long ago, 1976, so his work is still fairly recent.

01:06.840 --> 01:10.180
He'd been active in the field though years before he started writing, corresponding

01:10.180 --> 01:16.420
with authors and other fans, attending conventions, editing a fanzine, even starting a small publishing

01:16.420 --> 01:19.440
company, Mirage Press, to produce material on science fiction.

01:20.000 --> 01:22.340
But Chalker says he'd always planned on being a writer.

01:23.720 --> 01:25.720
I'd always known I was going to be a writer.

01:26.080 --> 01:28.140
I mean, there just was never any question in my mind.

01:28.680 --> 01:31.760
But it was just sort of something that you never really sat down and did.

01:31.860 --> 01:34.180
I used to play around with stories here and there.

01:35.460 --> 01:37.060
John Campbell was a big help.

01:39.100 --> 01:45.360
During the 60s, I would float ideas and fragments off him, and he would be very, very nice and

01:45.360 --> 01:46.660
tell me exactly what was wrong.

01:46.660 --> 01:52.720
Of course, what I've created everybody about John Campbell was that the man had been editing

01:52.720 --> 01:57.480
for 40 years, and he could put his finger on something and tell you exactly what you

01:57.480 --> 02:02.460
were doing wrong, and it was terribly infuriating to discover that he was right in almost every

02:02.460 --> 02:02.860
case.

02:04.000 --> 02:07.280
He saw why he did it from 39 until he died.

02:09.180 --> 02:15.820
And as a result of being able to have the help of people like Campbell and August Arilith

02:15.820 --> 02:22.500
and a lot of really established writers and editors in the field, I was able to get a good

02:22.500 --> 02:26.580
recognition of exactly what was required in the field.

02:27.660 --> 02:30.320
It just was a matter of sitting down and doing it.

02:31.240 --> 02:35.960
And fortunately, he did sit down and do it, publishing Jungle of Stars in 1976.

02:35.960 --> 02:45.980
So I sat on a typewriter, and there was really no question in my mind as to what I'd do first.

02:47.640 --> 02:51.460
I had been playing around with an idea for years and years and years.

02:52.300 --> 02:59.740
There's even a short, fancy version of it, 20 years old, called Jungle or Jungle of Stars.

03:00.800 --> 03:03.880
There were a lot of codewords, but Jungle was always in it.

03:05.040 --> 03:08.700
And I sat down and wrote the things.

03:09.240 --> 03:09.560
I wrote it.

03:10.080 --> 03:14.780
It had been around so long in my mind and in discussions and so on that there were just

03:14.780 --> 03:20.460
no problems, no resistance, no having to think it out or anything else.

03:21.440 --> 03:24.520
And I wrote it solidly in about two and a half, three weeks.

03:26.280 --> 03:27.940
And then sent it off.

03:29.540 --> 03:33.300
And it's a good old-fashioned type.

03:34.200 --> 03:37.240
It's a science fiction murder mystery.

03:38.880 --> 03:43.120
Very much at home in the old astounding analogs.

03:43.240 --> 03:46.740
And so I didn't even know if that's some modern touches to it.

03:52.400 --> 03:56.360
Some of his earlier contacts with people in the field of science fiction paid off.

03:56.360 --> 03:58.840
One of them, Judy Lindell Ray, bought the novel.

04:00.280 --> 04:10.580
Judy Lindell Ray, who had just become editor of Ballantyne, which was soon to have a science fiction line named after her,

04:13.180 --> 04:14.140
took a look at it.

04:14.480 --> 04:16.640
We'd known each other for about 15 years.

04:17.700 --> 04:24.700
And she put off reading it for quite a long time because she was afraid that if it was terrible and she said so,

04:24.700 --> 04:27.260
she'd blow our friendship or something.

04:27.900 --> 04:33.880
Finally she said, we got together at a convention and she admitted to me all this.

04:34.080 --> 04:35.780
She said, okay, I'll read it, but be prepared.

04:36.600 --> 04:41.280
And about four days later I get a phone call and she said, hey, this is great. I want to buy it.

04:42.740 --> 04:44.180
And that was the first sale.

04:45.940 --> 04:49.680
Since then, Chalker has published some 13 novels and he's still going strong.

04:50.180 --> 04:51.920
More with Jack Chalker next time.

