06:32.700 --> 06:39.300
A hike through a national park and a war game board, unlikely sources for a tremendously popular science fiction novel.

06:39.700 --> 06:43.180
The novel is Midnight at the Well of Souls. The author is Jack Chalker.

06:43.620 --> 06:48.160
The book concerns the Well World, an artificial planet constructed by a vanished civilization.

06:48.160 --> 06:53.840
The Well World is divided into 1560 separate environments, separate worlds really,

06:54.440 --> 06:57.340
each with its own climate, geography and intelligent inhabitants.

06:57.860 --> 07:01.660
Each division is shaped like a hexagon, and for that reason they're called hexes.

07:02.280 --> 07:07.420
Chalker was in an isolated village called Stahikin on the shore of Lake Chelan in Central Washington State

07:07.420 --> 07:09.180
when he got the idea for the Well World.

07:10.640 --> 07:14.920
I got to sitting by the lake that night and talking with some people.

07:15.880 --> 07:25.820
And I got the idea for this large world built by a long dead race, so on.

07:25.940 --> 07:28.380
And I didn't really have much of an idea of what it was.

07:29.200 --> 07:34.160
And they do have a service out of Stahikin that'll take you up to Trailhead.

07:35.260 --> 07:38.720
And so I went up to Trailhead and I wound up walking down.

07:38.980 --> 07:42.020
I'm a great hiker as long as the direction is down.

07:43.920 --> 07:48.500
I'm afraid I've never been to the bottom of the Grand Canyon because I can get down there but I can't get back up.

07:49.220 --> 07:52.000
But here was a trail that was tailor made for me.

07:52.140 --> 07:55.640
It was down the Cascades, all the way.

07:56.980 --> 08:04.120
So I took it and it took about 8 1 half hours to walk the whole distance.

08:06.900 --> 08:09.780
And during that time you go through eight climate zones.

08:10.220 --> 08:13.760
You start off in the snow, you wind up in a rainforest.

08:15.480 --> 08:17.720
And some of the changes are rather abrupt.

08:17.920 --> 08:22.840
You just go around to switch back and it just changes from one climate to another,

08:22.920 --> 08:28.240
each with its own different plants and insects and occasional mammals.

08:29.260 --> 08:30.780
Even the birds seem to be different.

08:31.000 --> 08:33.480
And I thought, yeah, this is how that big world would be like.

08:34.420 --> 08:39.040
So even though while I was on my way down I was kind of scribbling ideas.

08:40.920 --> 08:51.620
And I got the idea for this giant world composed of basically world-like different abrupt geography, climate, landforms.

08:52.240 --> 08:54.740
You name it, each with its own dominant race.

08:57.120 --> 09:04.420
By the time I hit bottom my head had pretty well worked out, although I didn't really know what the shape of the things were going to be.

09:05.780 --> 09:09.060
Back home in Maryland he got some help on the shape of the well world.

09:10.360 --> 09:18.640
I was discussing the idea with a science fiction fan named Ben Yellow, son of the Nobel winner, Rosalind Yellen.

09:18.640 --> 09:22.700
And he said, why don't you just use an Avalon Hill game board?

09:24.200 --> 09:26.060
And I thought, yeah, that would work.

09:26.560 --> 09:33.680
So we got out an Avalon Hill map, a war game map, and a little trusty calculator.

09:34.500 --> 09:40.260
We laid a grid of these hexagons around a roughly earth-sized world.

09:41.120 --> 09:43.440
And of course you cannot cover a sphere with hexagons.

09:43.440 --> 09:52.880
So that means we had the north zone and the south zone, which would be the embassy's entry and exit points that would cover our sphere.

09:53.740 --> 10:04.840
And then it was just simply a matter of sitting down, listing what was required to do, what kind of creatures and land, climate and so on.

10:04.840 --> 10:16.360
And I would have to do for the route of the story, dropping by Avalon Hill, which I lived very near at the time, picking up some blank maps and just working it out from there.

10:17.820 --> 10:22.280
What Chalker worked out turned into his best known novel, Midnight at the Well of Souls.

10:22.860 --> 10:26.720
It was so popular that it went out of print a few months after its initial press run.

10:27.040 --> 10:31.120
And Chalker has added four novels since then, making a five book series in the well world.

10:31.120 --> 10:37.220
The whole thing turned out to be a colorful and exciting epic on the origin of the universe and all of the creatures in it.

10:37.640 --> 10:39.900
It should fascinate any reader of science fiction.

10:40.380 --> 10:41.940
More on Jack Chalker next time.

