12:24.220 --> 12:28.640
The five novels in Jack Chalker's Well World series are based on a familiar science fiction concept.

12:28.640 --> 12:34.660
And that concept is the notion of a long dead race of superior beings whose artifacts are found by humans.

12:35.140 --> 12:38.980
But there are a couple of interesting twists given to this concept by Chalker.

12:39.560 --> 12:44.700
One twist is the principal artifact by the vanished race. It's a planet called the Well World.

12:45.220 --> 12:51.020
It's artificial, and its interior is a super computer that can transform matter into all sorts of living creatures.

12:51.020 --> 12:58.140
It's really a laboratory planet where species are created and tested before being transferred to various places throughout the universe.

12:58.540 --> 13:03.640
And the other twist is that the superior beings, called the Markovians, aren't actually gone.

13:04.320 --> 13:07.040
They just transformed themselves into other, more primitive beings.

13:07.600 --> 13:09.380
Chalker talks about the Markovians.

13:10.080 --> 13:12.860
They got to the point where they were gone, literally.

13:14.280 --> 13:19.360
Where their devices could conjure up anything they wanted, just with a mere thought of it.

13:21.280 --> 13:27.740
I since had it pointed out to me that they're sort of like the Crel and the old movie Forbidden Planet.

13:28.580 --> 13:30.700
And that they reach this Godhead status.

13:31.520 --> 13:36.960
But the Crel experiment failed because they couldn't control their passions.

13:36.960 --> 13:41.440
And the Markovian experiment succeeded, and they literally became gods.

13:41.920 --> 13:43.160
Then they became miserable.

13:44.180 --> 13:47.480
There was nothing left to attain. There was nothing left to know.

13:47.660 --> 13:55.240
There was nothing left to, you know, get a bunch of creatures that spent millions of years rising to this point.

13:55.360 --> 13:57.080
And they sit around and they say, is this all there is?

13:58.400 --> 14:01.500
At this point, the Markovians decided to start all over again.

14:02.280 --> 14:08.600
The idea of the great experiment came about was to redo it.

14:08.820 --> 14:16.520
To literally start the Markovians over from scratch with different kinds of creatures, different environments.

14:18.460 --> 14:20.780
With no real value system.

14:21.060 --> 14:24.600
I mean, they have to develop their own unique value systems. They do.

14:25.480 --> 14:32.000
And as a result, they're grown and they're tested on this laboratory world, the well world.

14:32.520 --> 14:41.260
And then they were the ones that worked, the ones that showed promise of survival, were then set into motion out throughout the universe.

14:42.340 --> 14:43.340
Including man.

14:45.860 --> 14:58.480
And they had the hope that eventually one of these races would reach a state of perfection that would not be empty or hollow.

14:59.360 --> 15:05.460
Now, I personally believe that when you reach that state, it is empty and hollow.

15:06.200 --> 15:14.640
But that's just my feeling other people might certainly do think differently.

15:16.700 --> 15:21.500
The Markovians create hundreds of different species. All intelligent, but all incredibly different.

15:21.980 --> 15:25.440
We asked Chalker how he gets ideas for creating such a variety of aliens.

15:26.940 --> 15:32.760
I used a variety of things. In some cases, a good pictorial natural history text.

15:32.760 --> 15:35.580
It'll give you more weird creatures than you've ever seen.

15:37.180 --> 15:38.600
Which can be modified.

15:40.420 --> 15:41.920
Some came out of mythology.

15:44.160 --> 15:46.620
Some came more or less direct out of Fantasia.

15:47.660 --> 15:48.860
Sources like that.

15:50.080 --> 15:54.020
And a few came out of comic book concepts.

15:55.260 --> 16:00.700
You know, you just brought them in from all over and you used basic shapes and basic types.

16:00.700 --> 16:09.000
And then you adjust them to what would happen if these were real, fendient, intelligent creatures.

16:10.600 --> 16:17.320
I found very, very little trouble in coming up with an enormous variety of them.

16:18.000 --> 16:23.680
I'm not sure whether I could come up with 1,560, which is the number I would have to to visit every hex in the world.

16:24.480 --> 16:27.440
But I've had no trouble coming up with the 2,300 so far.

