Before you became a best-selling Science Fiction author, Jack Chalker was an avid fan who built an amateur fanzine into a Science Fiction Publishing Company.

18:25.980 --> 18:31.200
Chalker started the fanzine in his early teens as a way of making contacts in the field of Science Fiction

18:31.200 --> 18:34.020
and with the possibility of making a little money at it.

18:35.320 --> 18:44.540
That basically was the reason we started with the fanzine, which was run off actually at a school, the beginning, because we didn't have anything else.

18:47.220 --> 18:52.200
And he'd got some reasonably good reactions, so I started building up from there.

18:52.200 --> 19:02.700
While I was doing that, actually, I had correspondence already with enormous numbers of people, both professional and fan.

19:03.600 --> 19:10.320
I had so much correspondence, I can't believe how many people I was contacting on a regular basis.

19:10.320 --> 19:26.020
And so I started tapping them and created the fanzine Mirage in the addition of a $40 surplus mini-graph in an old store, which I still own, by the way, and which still works.

19:27.860 --> 19:31.620
I was able to start putting out a fanzine called Mirage.

19:32.860 --> 19:38.740
The fanzine was successful because of its high quality, and it led into a small publishing company, Mirage Press.

19:40.520 --> 19:46.640
I was serious and constructive at the same time that everybody else was being just sort of kid hobbyist.

19:47.460 --> 19:57.540
I really had a magazine that discussed the literature, discussed the writers and so on past and present, and at a time when very few of these were coming out.

19:57.540 --> 20:04.360
And so I attracted a rather large audience of collectors and professional writers and artists and so on.

20:05.040 --> 20:22.860
And I was able to create out of that the Mirage Press, which started off, again, as a mini-graph publication, and then later grew as capital grew into a hardcover and paperback, quality paperback publishing house.

20:25.140 --> 20:28.260
Chalker says that Mirage Press was successful from the start.

20:29.500 --> 20:33.780
I started off with a bibliography of HP Lovecraft, which I did myself.

20:34.520 --> 20:58.700
Put it together, mini-graphed it with the help of Auguste Aralith, who owned the rights to the HP Lovecraft material at the time, and sold it for what in 1960 was a horrendous fee of a $1, and we sold a hundred of them.

21:00.420 --> 21:08.620
Mirage Press publishes non-fiction materials such as bibliographies and critical studies of authors. Chalker leaves the publishing of fiction to the large companies.

21:28.800 --> 21:39.500
You really have to promote fiction, whereas non-fiction and reference material is always, there's always a heavy market and there's been a growing market for it.

21:40.020 --> 21:42.220
And so I concentrated in that end.

21:43.060 --> 21:53.800
And we came up with some rather successful books, Guide to Middle Earth, which in its Valentine's form, which I still own a piece of, is still selling well in Atlasi Fantasy.

21:57.060 --> 22:02.200
We did three books on sword and sorcery fiction before the comic books discovered Conan.

22:03.900 --> 22:17.480
And occasionally we did rather odd materials, such as a collection of all of the Ferdinand Fakut bad puns that have been published over the years, this kind of thing.

22:18.600 --> 22:23.760
Mostly though we were serious reference works and we still have a number of them that are standard.

